# For code, scroll down
So, guys, if you approach it in the recursive way,  (Top-down) you would most likely get an memorey limit exceeded error, So, here i'll explain my intuition behind the logic as well as how i converted it to bottom up and a suggestion foor an even optimised solution.

So practically we need words in increasing order of their length,, that indicates we can sort our words list,
after sorting it
basically problem breaks down to two major conditions
you wanna include this current word, or you dont

so if you dont want to include the current word, simply  explore for the word in next index
then, in case your current word meets the criteria of string chain, i.e 1 letter would be extra than its immediate preious, and rest all are letters match(in same order), then you can proceed by including this element and moving on to next index,
now you canuse your dp to store the maximum of either including or not including, and thus return.


now due to the limits in recursive call, you would probably get an error, so in the bottom up way :
prev acts as row, so from lastword to the beginning iterate
curr acts as column take it from last word to word just behind after prev
rest the logic remains same

You could further optimise it by taking 2 1d dps
If our dp depends on current row and just the previous row, we can use 2 dps, one for curr iteration and 1 storing values of previous iteration, here just make the row iterations as curr and column iterations as previous and just make changes accordingly.

If you feel something can be added on , I'm open to suggestions.

```
class Solution:
    def longestStrChain(self, words: List[str]) -> int:
        words.sort(key = lambda x: len(x))

        dp = {}
        @lru_cache(None)
        def iSvalidInclusion(word1,word2):
            if not (len(word2)==len(word1)+1):   
                return False
            i =0
            count =1

            while i<len(word1):

