solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Look at the constraint ```1 <= words[i].length <= 16```. There are many ways of DP.

Varying the ```words[i]``` is easier and quicker! In fact there are len(words[i]) substrings with length=len(words[i])-1 

Use an array over ```unordered_set<string, int> mp```

The index for ```mp[i]``` denote the length of string.
# Why not just unordered_set<string, int>?
Although the C++ unodered_map is in average O(1) for inserting & updating an element, but in worst case it is a linear time O(k) where k=size of the container. So breaking it into an array of smaller unordered sets may save time! 

The array for unordered_maps may be changed into array for maps when n is small, and it might make code for small n more efficient.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. ```vector<unordered_map<string, int>>``` is a declaration that defines a vector containing elements of type ```unordered_map<string, int>```. Each element in the vector is an unordered map that associates strings with integer values.
2. ```mp``` is the name of the vector of unordered maps.
3. Vector ```mp``` is initialized with 17 elements (length of 0~16). Each element represents a different word length.
4. if ```mp[5]["apple"]``` is 3, it means that the longest chain that can be formed using words of length 5 includes "apple" and two other words.
5. ```vector<unordered_map<string, int>> mp(17);```is used to maintain a data structure that organizes words by their lengths and keeps track of the longest chain that can be formed for each word length. It's a crucial part of the dynamic programming approach used to solve the problem of finding the longest string chain.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(len(word)*16+n\log n)=O(n\log n)$
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(len(word))
# Code runtime 54ms
```
class Solution {
public:
    int longestStrChain(vector<string>& words) {
        int n = words.size();
        if (n == 1) return 1;
        sort(words.begin(), words.end(), [&](string& x, string& y) {
            return x.size() < y.size(); 
        });
        vector<unordered_map<string, int>> mp(17);
        for (auto& w : words)
            mp[w.size()][w] = 1;

        int ans = 0;

        for (auto& w : words) {
            int sz = w.size();
            if (sz == 1) continue;
            for (int i = 0; i < sz; i++) {
                string w2 = w.substr(0, i) + w.substr(i+1); 
                if (mp[sz-1].count(w2) != 0) {
