solutions.content:
### Solution
Have two maps 
1. Map of string size and set of string of that size
2. Map of each string and the longest chain formed till that string

Start loop from the size = lowestWordSize+1. 
For every word is current size, check if the setOfStrings with size-1 has a chain word
If yes, update lenTillCurrentWord = 1 + lenTillClippedWord

Return max of lenTillCurrentWord

##### Time Complexity = O(N*S*S)
##### Space Complexity = O(N*S)

```java
class Solution {
    public int longestStrChain(String[] words) {
        int maxChainSize = 1;
        int startSize = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        Map<Integer, Set<String>> sizeMap = new HashMap<>();
        Map<String, Integer> sizeTillStringMap = new HashMap<>();

        for (String word: words){
            int size = word.length();
            startSize = Math.min(startSize, size);

            Set<String> setOfStrings = sizeMap.getOrDefault(size, new HashSet<>());
            setOfStrings.add(word);
            sizeMap.put(size, setOfStrings);
        }

        while(sizeMap.containsKey(++startSize)){
            Set<String> prevListOfStrings = sizeMap.get(startSize-1);
            for (String word: sizeMap.get(startSize)){
                int maxLen = 1;
                for (int i=0; i<word.length(); i++){
                    String clippedWord = word.substring(0, i) + word.substring(i+1, word.length());
                    if (prevListOfStrings.contains(clippedWord)){
                        maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, sizeTillStringMap.getOrDefault(clippedWord,1) + 1);
                    }
                }
                sizeTillStringMap.put(word, maxLen);
                maxChainSize = Math.max(maxChainSize, maxLen);
            }
        }

        return maxChainSize;
    }
}
```

