# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem requires finding the longest word chain possible from a given list of words. A word chain is a sequence of words where each word is a predecessor of the next word, which means you can insert exactly one letter anywhere in a word to make it equal to the next word. To solve this problem, we can use dynamic programming to find the longest chain length for each word.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Sort the given list of words based on their lengths. This sorting is important because we want to process shorter words before longer ones, ensuring that we have information about potential predecessors when processing longer words.

2. Initialize a dp (dynamic programming) map to store the length of the longest chain for each word. Initialize a variable maxLength to keep track of the maximum chain length found.

3. Iterate through each word in the sorted order:

4. Initialize currentLength to 1, as a single word forms a chain of length 1.
For each possible predecessor of the current word (by removing one character at a time), check if the predecessor is in the dp map.
If the predecessor is in the map, update currentLength to be the maximum of its current value and the length of the chain for the predecessor (from the dp map) plus 1.
Update the dp map for the current word with the calculated currentLength.

5. Update maxLength to be the maximum of its current value and the currentLength for the current word.

6. Continue this process for all words.

7. Finally, return the maxLength as the length of the longest word chain.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Sorting the words takes O(N log N), where N is the number of words.
The main loop iterates through each word, and for each word, it generates all possible predecessors by removing characters. This inner loop can take up to O(L) time, where L is the maximum length of a word.
Therefore, the overall time complexity is O(N log N + NL), which simplifies to O(NL + N log N).
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
1. We use a dp map to store the chain lengths for each word, which can take up to O(N) space.
2. Other variables used in the algorithm have constant space requirements.
3. Hence, the overall space complexity is O(N).
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int longestStrChain(vector<string>& words) {
        // Sort the words by their length
        sort(words.begin(), words.end(), [](const string& a, const string& b) {
            return a.size() < b.size();
        });

        unordered_map<string, int> dp; // Stores the length of the longest chain for each word

        int maxLength = 1; // Initialize the maximum length of the chain

        // Iterate through each word in the sorted order
        for (const string& word : words) {
            int currentLength = 1; // Initialize the chain length for the current word

            // Generate all possible predecessors of the current word
            for (int i = 0; i < word.size(); ++i) {
                string predecessor = word.substr(0, i) + word.substr(i + 1);

                // Check if the predecessor is in the dp map
                if (dp.count(predecessor)) {
                    currentLength = max(currentLength, dp[predecessor] + 1);
                }
            }

            // Update the dp map for the current word
            dp[word] = currentLength;

            // Update the maximum length of the chain
            maxLength = max(maxLength, currentLength);
        }

        return maxLength;
    }
};

```

