solutions.content:
You just have to come up with a logic. Suppose we have [1,3,5] the element that the array gets changed to is 3, and if its [1,3,5,7] it would be 4. Technically it will be the median value(3 in case of [1,3,5] and (3+5)/2 in case of [1,3,5,7]). Similary in case of [1,3,5,7,11,13] it would be 6. On the whole , if we observe carefully the median value is nothing but the size of the array n. The number of operations would be the sum of values obtained by subtracting the median from right half of the array or subtracting the left half array from median. To understand you can do it by hand. 

```
class Solution {
    public int minOperations(int n) {
        int median = n, sum = 0;
        while(2*n - 1 > median){
            sum += (2*n - 1) - median;
            n--;
        }
        return sum;        
    }
}
```

